<p class="lead">On March 15, 2026, Coimbatore police mounted cordon and search operations across several locations in the city and its periphery, sealing pockets briefly while teams verified identities, checked premises for suspicious material and spoke to residents about election-season risks. Framed as part of Tamil Nadu’s wider poll security architecture, the exercise sat alongside flying squads, static surveillance teams and routine beat policing under the Model Code of Conduct for the 2026 Legislative Assembly election. For a city that prides itself on industrial order and relatively low violent-crime rates compared with national metros, the operations were as much about deterrence—signalling that organised intimidation or stockpiling of contraband would face scrutiny—as about immediate seizures.</p>

<p>Cordon and search is a police tactic with a long lineage: outer perimeters stop movement in and out while inner teams work door-to-door or shop-to-shop. Legal authority, proportionality and respect for dignity are non-negotiable; trained officers are expected to explain the purpose, avoid gratuitous damage, and escalate only when intelligence or plain-view evidence justifies it. In election season, such drills are often intensified because inducements—cash, liquor, freebies—tend to move through networks that rely on ordinary-looking neighbourhoods and commercial fronts.</p>

